<p>I'm using embedded Youtube videos (iframe), but have a problem with the thumbnail (seen before playing the video) being very lowres on (some?) mobile devices.</p>  <p>For example, paste this url into your desktop browser: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/embed/MbhVgK0WgAE?list=PLnDj4GODT_Qq_6bgnLVAlLAlUsTtRuW6Y" rel="nofollow">https://www.youtube.com/embed/MbhVgK0WgAE?list=PLnDj4GODT_Qq_6bgnLVAlLAlUsTtRuW6Y</a></p>  <p>I'm using a retina MacBook Pro. Refresh the browser using different widths to see how the thumbnail properly changes, the best being <code>maxresdefault.jpg</code>.</p>  <p>Now go to the same URL on your smartphone (I'm using a Nexus 6). Regardless off if I use portrait or landscape the used thumbnail is <code>hqdefault.jpg</code> which is very lowres, extremely blurry text for example.</p>  <p>So the Nexus 6, having a resolution of 2560x1440 prefers <a href="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/MbhVgK0WgAE/hqdefault.jpg" rel="nofollow">hqdefault.jpg</a> over both <a href="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/MbhVgK0WgAE/sddefault.jpg" rel="nofollow">sddefault.jpg</a> and <a href="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/MbhVgK0WgAE/maxresdefault.jpg" rel="nofollow">maxresdeafult.jpg</a>.</p>  <p>Is there a bug with embedded iframes and HiDPI devices or is there a way, which I haven't found yet, to prefer higher resolution thumbnails by default? Or perhaps something else I'm doing wrong.</p>  <p>All suggestions are appreciated.</p>